<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-01-13T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-01-13T07:00:00-05:00" n="414" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d414">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5942: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-01-13T20:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">January 13,
                                        1925—8 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received January 13—9:35
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>22. My telegram number 14, January 12, 4 p.m.<note n="10" xml:id="d414fn10">Not printed.</note> Announcing his departure from
                            Tientsin for Mukden, Chang Tso-lin made following significant statement:
                            “All my troops will also be instructed to return to Mukden
                            successively.”</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>